    "Our study yields important theoretical takeaways about the civic role of private schooling and religious schools.",
    "Writing about the private school choice movement, political theorist Stephen Macedo (2003, pp. 57-58) states: Many [parents] are desperate to get a decent education for their children, and they want help to pay for a religious education…because those institutions are thought to provide a superior education, a safer environment, and a more coherent moral framework that will better promote the public virtues and values needed by young adults and future citizens nowadays.",
    "The findings of our meta-analysis are consistent with Macedo's claims.",
    "Religious schooling appears to increase civic outcomes in comparison to its secular counterpart, whether public or private.",
    "Even for the outcome of political tolerance, which, arguably, is the toughest test for religious schooling effects on civics, our analysis suggests that the average effect of religious schooling is, at worst, null."
